<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="http://talkirish.com/utility/FeedStylesheets/rss.xsl" media="screen"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:slash="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/" xmlns:wfw="http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/"><channel><title>The Irish Language - Grammar, Pronunciation, Games, Myths, Poetry and more</title><link>http://talkirish.com/forums/40.aspx</link><description>A great place to discuss Irish grammar, pronunciation, and vocabulary.  You'll also find lots of help and information on Irish translations, Irish myths and legends, and Irish poetry. And here's where we have some Irish word games and lots of useful tips on language learning.</description><dc:language>en</dc:language><generator>CommunityServer 2008 SP1 (Build: 30619.63)</generator><item><title>Re: Agreement of adjectives</title><link>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/10261.aspx</link><pubDate>Sun, 18 May 2014 18:12:58 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">0644754f-ff87-49dd-b5e3-0e104f790f4a:10261</guid><dc:creator>seano</dc:creator><slash:comments>0</slash:comments><comments>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/10261.aspx</comments><wfw:commentRss>http://talkirish.com/forums/commentrss.aspx?SectionID=40&amp;PostID=10261</wfw:commentRss><description>&lt;p&gt;An adjective only takes this form if it comes directly after a noun. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Is bean dheas &amp;iacute;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;T&amp;aacute; fuinneog mh&amp;oacute;r os cionn an dorais.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Is ollscoil bhre&amp;aacute; &amp;iacute; sin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But T&amp;aacute; an bhean sin deas, t&amp;aacute; an fhuinneog sin m&amp;oacute;r and t&amp;aacute; an ollscoil sin (go) bre&amp;aacute;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hope this helps!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description></item><item><title>Agreement of adjectives</title><link>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/10259.aspx</link><pubDate>Sun, 18 May 2014 17:46:43 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">0644754f-ff87-49dd-b5e3-0e104f790f4a:10259</guid><dc:creator>acork</dc:creator><slash:comments>0</slash:comments><comments>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/10259.aspx</comments><wfw:commentRss>http://talkirish.com/forums/commentrss.aspx?SectionID=40&amp;PostID=10259</wfw:commentRss><description>&lt;p&gt;There is one example of agreement of adjectives that I&amp;#39;m not sure about. If I want to say &amp;quot;Her mother is nice&amp;quot; would I say &amp;quot;T&amp;aacute; a m&amp;aacute;thair deas&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;T&amp;aacute; a m&amp;aacute;thair dheas&amp;quot;. I know that &amp;quot;m&amp;aacute;thair&amp;quot; is a feminie noun but I&amp;#39;m not sure if the adjective following it is lenited when the noun itself isn&amp;#39;t. Go raibh maith agat.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>